{"title_page": "England Coast Path", "text_new": "{{short description|A hiking path in England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\nThe '''England Coast Path''' is a proposed long-distance [[National Trail]] which will follow the coastline of [[England]]. When complete, it will be 2,795 miles (4,500 kilometres) in length.<ref name=\"EnglandCoastPath\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/england-coast-path |title=English Coast Path |publisher=nationaltrail.co.uk |access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:English ceremonial counties 1998.svg|thumb|right|When complete, the England Coast Path will follow the whole coastline of England (with county boundaries shown)]]\n[[File:swcoastpath.ilfracombe.arp.750pix.jpg|thumb|left|Part of the [[South West Coast Path]] near [[Ilfracombe]], [[North Devon]]]]\n\nThe trail is being implemented by [[Natural England]], a [[non-departmental public body]] of the [[UK government]] responsible for ensuring that England's natural environment is protected and improved. It also has a responsibility to help people enjoy, understand and access the [[natural environment]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/natural-england |title=Natural England |publisher=gov.uk |access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref> Although various National trails already existed along England's coast, the first stretch of the official England Coast Path was opened at Weymouth Bay in Dorset in 2012.<ref>[https://www.cicerone.co.uk/the-england-coast-path-the-challenge-of-plotting-a-path-by-the-sea Andrew McCloy, \"The England Coast Path: The challenge of plotting a path by the sea\" 6 May 2018 Cicerone]</ref>\n\nIn December 2014 the UK Government, encouraged by the success of the [[Wales Coast Path]], announced that more than \u00a35 million of additional funding was being committed over the following 5 years, to complete the Path by 2020, a decade earlier than would have otherwise been possible.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ramblers.org.uk/news/news/2014/september/england-coast-path-in-sight.aspx |title=England Coast Path in sight! |date=3 September 2014 |publisher=Ramblers |access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Progress\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/453171/coastal-access-england-map.pdf |title=Coastal Access Completion by 2020 \u2013 Provisional Timings and Stretches |publisher=Natural England |date=1 December 2015 |accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref> \nIn the [[UK]] [[Right_of_way#Foreshore|public access]] to the [[foreshore]], below the line marking [[high tide]], has existed for a long time. The intertidal zone is generally deemed to be owned by the [[The Crown|Crown]] although there are some exceptions. In England ownership of land extends only to the [[High water mark]], and [[The Crown]] is deemed to own what lies below it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udallaw.com/|title=S.O.U.L.|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref> \n\nBececause of a European court judgement in April 2018 regarding environmentally protected sites, progress has slowed, though Natural England hope to open \"as much of the England Coast Path as it can by 2020\".<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast#overview-of-progress \"Improving public access to the coast\", England Coast Path, Government of the UK]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Gristhorpe Cliff Tops on the Cleveland Way.jpg|thumb|right|[[Gristhorpe]] Cliff Tops on the [[Cleveland Way]],  [[North York Moors National Park]].]]\n\nThe final section of a long distance coastal footpath running {{convert|630|mi|km|adj=off}} around the [[South West Coast Path|southwest coast of England]], through Somerset, Devon, Cornwall, Devon and Dorset (walking anti-clockwise) was designated as a [[National Trail]] in 1978.<ref name=\"CA2003\">{{Cite web |url=http://195.92.230.86/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |title=Coast Path is a \u00a3300M Money Spinner for the South West |last=Countryside Agency |date=25 September 2003 |publisher=Countryside Agency |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20081205014058/http://www.countryside.gov.uk/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |archive-date=5 December 2008 |access-date=1 February 2008 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sections were opened earlier: in Cornwall, 1973, South Devon and Dorset Paths, 1974, Exmoor Coast, 1975.<ref>[https://www.southwestcoastpath.org.uk/about-coast-path/about-us/our-history/ ]\"Our History\", Southwest Coastal Path Association]</ref> \n\nPrior to this, in Wales, the [[Pembrokeshire Coast Path]] had been opened in 1970. Following the establishment of the [[Pembrokeshire Coast National Park]] in 1952, Welsh naturalist and author [[Ronald Lockley]] surveyed a route around the coast. <ref name=\"PembrokeshgireCoastal\">{{cite book |title=The Pembrokeshire Coastal Path: From Amroth to St Dogmaels: A Practical Guide for Walkers |first1=Dennis |last1=Kelsall |first2=Jan |last2=Kelsall |publisher=Cicerone Press |year=2005 |edition=2nd |isbn=978-1852843786}}</ref> Lockley's report for the [[Countryside Commission]] in 1953 was welcomed and broadly adopted. Some sections of the walk were existing rights-of-way, but the majority were in private hands,  necessitating negotiation. Most landowners were in favour, and many benefitted from the erection of new fencing.  Even today, however, the path in places detours from the obvious line where landowners were unwilling to accept a new right-of-way across their land.<ref name=\"PembrokeshireCoast\">{{cite book| title=Pembrokeshire Coast Path |first=Brian |last=John |publisher=Aurum Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1845137823}}</ref>\n\n===Right to roam===\nin 2000 the Government legislated to introduce a limited ''right to roam'', without compensation for landowners. The [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]] (CROW) was gradually implemented from 2000 onwards to give the general public the conditional right to walk in certain areas of the English and Welsh countryside, including coastal land. Developed land, gardens and certain other areas are specifically excluded from the right of access. Agricultural land is accessible if it falls within one of the categories described in the Act. People exercising the right of access have certain duties to respect other people's rights to manage the land, and to protect nature. The new rights were introduced region by region through England with completion in 2005. Maps showing accessible areas exist.\n\n===Legal background===\n[[File:Cliffs of Dover.jpg|thumb|[[Cliffs of Dover]] on the [[Saxon Shore Way]]]]\nThe England Coast Path has been possible because of the introduction of a UK law, the Right of Coastal Access (Part 9 of the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009)<ref name=\"auto\">{{citation|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/5327964912746496?category=50007|title=Coastal Access - Natural England's Approved Scheme, 2013|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast#map |publisher=www.gov.uk |title= England Coast Path: improving public access to the coast|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> both along the England Coast Path and, usually, over the associated \u2018coastal margin\u2019.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.gov.uk/manage-your-land-on-the-england-coast-path|publisher= www.gov.uk|title= Manage your land on the England Coast Path|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nNatural England's Coastal Access Scheme was approved by the [[Secretary of State (United Kingdom)|Secretary of State]] on 9 July 2013 under section 298(2) of the [[Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009]], and presented to Parliament pursuant to section 298(6) of the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe first instance of this new law was implemented on a stretch of the English coast at [[Weymouth Bay]] on 29 June 2012.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/328985/iow-consult-sum-resp.pdf|title=Weymouth Bay|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThis includes \u2013 where appropriate \u2013 any land, other than the trail itself, which forms part of the coastal margin and which has public rights of access along the way. This is known as \u2018spreading room\u2019. However, this does not include any right to enter private houses and gardens or [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] land. The new right of Coastal Access also includes 'roll back', namely that if a section of coast erodes, the path will move back accordingly.<ref name=\"EnglandCoastPath\" />\n\n==Existing coastal trails==\n[[Image:Bamburgh2006.jpg|left|thumb|[[Bamburgh Castle]], on the [[Northumberland]] Coast Trail]]\n{{Main article|List of long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom|National Trails}}\nExisting coastal trails in England will be incorporated into the England Coast Path.  There is, however, work to be done in upgrading and standardizing access and signage on these.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast \"Improving access to the coast\", Natural England].</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of some of the existing coastal paths. For information of others details can be found on the [https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/public/ldp_public_home.php Long Distance Walkers Associations web page].\n\n* [[Bournemouth Coast Path]]: {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[Cleveland Way]]: {{convert|110|mi|km|adj=off}}; only part of the Cleveland Way is coastal. First proposed in the 1930s A formal proposal was submitted in 1953.<ref>The Cleveland Way. Bill Cowley. Dalesman Publishing 1969</ref> The trail was officially opened in 1969. It was the second official [[National Trails|National Trail]] to be opened.<ref>[http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/ClevelandWay/text.asp?PageId=2 About this Trail - Cleveland Way - National Trails<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n* [[Cumbria Coastal Way]]: {{convert|185|mi|km|adj=off}}\n*[[Durham]] Coastal Footpath (18 km/11 miles) passes through or close to [[Seaham Harbour]], [[Dawdon]], [[Easington, County Durham|Easington]], [[Castle Eden Dene|Dene Mouth]], and [[Blackhall]].<ref>[https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Durham+Coastal+Footpath \"Durham Coast Path\", Long Distance Walkers Association]</ref>\n* [[Isle of Wight Coastal Path]]: {{convert|67|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[Lancashire Coastal Way]]: {{convert|66|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[Norfolk Coast Path]]: {{convert|45|mi|km|adj=off}}. It was opened in 1986 and covers the North Norfolk Coast AONB ([[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]).\n* The [[Northumberland Coast]] Path runs 101 km/63 miles along the coast from [[Cresswell, Northumberland|Cresswell]] as far as [[Bamburgh]]. before heading inland to [[Belford, Northumberland|Belford]] and the Kyloe Hills, which offer panoramic coastal views. From here it joins [[St. Cuthbert's Way]] and returns to the coast at the causeway to [[Lindisfarne|Holy Island]] before continuing to [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], close to the Scottish border. It is part of the European [[North Sea Trail]].<ref>[https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Northumberland+Coast+Path \"Northumberland Coast Path\", Long Distance Walkers Association]</ref>\n* [[Saxon Shore Way]]: {{convert|163|mi|km|adj=off}}. The Saxon Shore Way was originally opened in 1980, but has since been re-established, and in parts re-routed and extended.<ref name=\"Trails and Paths\">{{cite web|url=http://www.walkingpages.co.uk/trails_paths/LDP_saxonshoreway.htm|title=The Saxon Shore Way|publisher=Walking Pages - Trails and Paths|page=1|accessdate=3 April 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080216225018/http://www.walkingpages.co.uk/trails_paths/LDP_saxonshoreway.htm |archivedate = 16 February 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Solent Way]]: {{convert|60|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[South West Coast Path]]: {{convert|630|mi|km|adj=off}}. The final section of the path was designated as a National Trail in 1978.<ref name=\"CA2003\">{{Cite web |url=http://195.92.230.86/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |title=Coast Path is a \u00a3300M Money Spinner for the South West |last=Countryside Agency |date=25 September 2003 |publisher=Countryside Agency |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20081205014058/http://www.countryside.gov.uk/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |archive-date=5 December 2008 |access-date=1 February 2008 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Suffolk Coast Path]]: {{convert|50|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[West Somerset Coast Path]]: {{convert|58|mi|km|adj=off}}. In March 2016 the path was extended to run from [[Brean Down]] to [[Minehead]].<ref>{{cite web|title=England Coast Path new stretch opens in Somerset|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-35810243|publisher=BBC|accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Work in progress===\n[[Image:Head banner cropped golf2.jpg|350px|thumb|[[St Bees Head]], [[Cumbria Coastal Way]]]]\n\nSee the official website for the current situations: [https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast Natural England]. Some [[right of way]] and foreshore access may already exist.\n\n===Linked trails===\n\n*At the border with [[Wales]] it will link to the [[Wales Coast Path]], which was fully opened on 5 May 2012, and comprises an {{convert|870|mi|adj=on}} coastal walking route from [[Chepstow]] in the south to [[Queensferry, Flintshire|Queensferry]] in the north.<ref name=\"BBCNews20111017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-15283462|work=BBC News Wales |title= All-Wales coast path nears completion|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/uk/a-welsh-wander-tackle-the-870-milelong-wales-coast-path-a-little-at-a-time-7712412.html|work=The Independent|title= Wales Coast Path at a glance|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n*[[Offa's Dyke Path]], a {{convert|177|mi|km|adj=on}} non-coastal route, also links the England Coast Path at its Welsh border, largely following the line of the remnants of [[Offa's Dyke]], fairly close to the boundary between England and Wales.\n\n==outline of the route==\nNatural England has divided the coast into 66 sections for planning purposes. The sections fall into 5 categories:\n* England Coast Path and associated access rights now open\n* Approved but not yet open\n* Work in progress\n* Estimated start 2016\u201317\n* Estimated start 2017\u201318\n\nThe sections (working anti-clockwise round England from the southern end of the Welsh border and using Natural England's areas) comprise:<ref name=\"Progress\" />\n\n{{Flatlist|\n* '''Area 11: [[Somerset]]'''\n** [[Aust]] to [[Brean Down]]\n** Brean Down to [[Minehead]]\n* '''Area 12: [[Devon]] and [[Cornwall]]'''\n** Minehead to [[Combe Martin]]\n** [[South West Coast Path]]\n** [[St Anthony in Roseland|St Anthony]] to [[Cremyll]]\n** [[Kingswear]] to [[Lyme Regis]]\n* '''Area 13: [[Dorset]], [[Hampshire]] and [[Isle of Wight]]'''\n** Lyme Regis to [[Rufus Castle]]\n** Rufus Castle to [[Lulworth Cove]]\n** Lulworth Cove to [[Christchurch, Dorset|Christchurch]]\n** Christchurch to [[Calshot]]\n** Calshot to [[Gosport]]\n** [[Isle of Wight]]\n** Gosport to South Hayling Island\n* '''Area 14: [[Sussex]] and [[Kent]]'''\n** [[South Hayling]] Island to East Head\n** East Head to [[Shoreham-by-Sea|Shoreham]]\n** Shoreham to [[Eastbourne]]\n** Eastbourne to [[Camber, East Sussex|Camber]]\n** Camber to [[Folkestone]]\n** Folkestone to [[Ramsgate]]\n** Ramsgate to [[Whitstable]]\n** [[Isle of Sheppey]]\n** Whitstable to [[Iwade]]\n** Iwade to [[Grain, Kent|Grain]]\n** Grain to [[Gravesend]]\n* '''Area 8: [[Essex]]'''\n** Gravesend to [[Southend-on-Sea]]\n** Southend to [[Wallasea Island]]\n** [[Foulness]], [[Potton Island|Potton]] and Wallasea Island\n** Wallasea Island to [[Burnham-on-Crouch]]\n** Burnham-on-Crouch to [[Maldon, Essex|Maldon]]\n** Maldon to [[Salcott]]\n** [[Mersea Island]]\n** Salcott to [[Jaywick]]\n** Jaywick to [[Harwich]]\n* '''Area 9: [[Suffolk]] and [[Norfolk]]'''\n** Harwich to [[Shotley Gate]]\n** Shotley Gate to [[Felixstowe]]\n** [[Felixstowe Ferry]] to [[Bawdsey]]\n** Bawdsey to [[Aldeburgh]]\n** Aldeburgh to [[Hopton-on-Sea]]\n** Hopton-on-Sea to [[Sea Palling]]\n** Sea Palling to [[Weybourne, Norfolk|Weybourne]]\n** Weybourne to [[Hunstanton]]\n** Hunstanton to [[Sutton Bridge]]\n* '''Area 5: [[Lincolnshire]]'''\n** Sutton Bridge to [[Skegness]]\n** Skegness to [[Donna Nook]]\n** '''''Area 3''''' ([[Yorkshire]])\n** Donna Nook to [[Humber Bridge]]\n** Humber Bridge to [[Kilnsea]]\n** Kilnsea to [[Filey Brigg]]\n** Filey Brigg to [[Tees Newport Bridge|Newport Bridge]]\n* '''Area 1: [[County Durham|Durham]], [[Tyne & Wear]] and [[Northumberland]]'''\n** Newport Bridge to North Gare\n** North Gare to South Bents\n** South Bents to [[Amble]]\n** Amble to [[Bamburgh]]\n** [[Lindisfarne]]\n** Bamburgh to [[Anglo-Scottish border|Scottish border]]\n** '''''Area 2''''' ([[Cumbria]])\n** [[Lindisfarne|Gretna]] to [[Allonby]]\n** Allonby to [[Whitehaven]]\n** Whitehaven to [[Silecroft]]\n** Silecroft to [[Silverdale, Lancashire|Silverdale]]\n* '''Area 4: [[Lancashire]] and [[Merseyside]]'''\n** [[Walney Island]]\n** Silverdale to [[Cleveleys]]\n** Cleveleys to [[Pier Head]], [[Liverpool]]\n** [[Birkenhead]] to Welsh Border\n}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* The [[E9 European long distance path]] or European Coastal Path (French: ''Sentier Europ\u00e9en du Littoral'') is one of the [[European long-distance paths]], running for {{convert|5000|km}} from [[Cabo de S\u00e3o Vicente]] in [[Portugal]] to [[Narva-J\u00f5esuu]] in [[Estonia]]. UK Section [[Dover]] to [[Plymouth]] (both ferry ports).\n* [[Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[North Sea Trail]]. In England partner areas are [[Northumberland]], and the [[North York Moors]]\n* [[Scottish Coastal Way]]\n\n==References== \n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast England Coast Path: improving public access to the coast] Natural England. Retrieved 20 January 2017\n* [http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/england-coast-path England Coast Path] National Trails. Retrieved 20 January 2017\n\n{{Coastal paths of Britain}}\n{{UK Trails}}\n\n[[Category:Coastal paths in England]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A hiking path in England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2017}}\nThe '''England Coast Path''' is a proposed long-distance [[National Trail]] which will follow the coastline of [[England]]. When complete, it will be 2,795 miles (4,500 kilometres) in length.<ref name=\"EnglandCoastPath\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/england-coast-path |title=English Coast Path |publisher=nationaltrail.co.uk |access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:English ceremonial counties 1998.svg|thumb|right|When complete, the England Coast Path will follow the whole coastline of England (with county boundaries shown)]]\n[[File:swcoastpath.ilfracombe.arp.750pix.jpg|thumb|left|Part of the [[South West Coast Path]] near [[Ilfracombe]]]]\n\nThe trail is being implemented by [[Natural England]], a [[non-departmental public body]] of the [[UK government]] responsible for ensuring that England's natural environment is protected and improved. It also has a responsibility to help people enjoy, understand and access the [[natural environment]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/natural-england |title=Natural England |publisher=gov.uk |access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref> Although various National trails already existed along England's coast, the first stretch of the official England Coast Path was opened at Weymouth Bay in Dorset in 2012.<ref>[https://www.cicerone.co.uk/the-england-coast-path-the-challenge-of-plotting-a-path-by-the-sea Andrew McCloy, \"The England Coast Path: The challenge of plotting a path by the sea\" 6 May 2018 Cicerone]</ref>\n\nIn December 2014 the UK Government, encouraged by the success of the [[Wales Coast Path]], announced that more than \u00a35 million of additional funding was being committed over the following 5 years, to complete the Path by 2020, a decade earlier than would have otherwise been possible.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ramblers.org.uk/news/news/2014/september/england-coast-path-in-sight.aspx |title=England Coast Path in sight! |date=3 September 2014 |publisher=Ramblers |access-date=4 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Progress\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/453171/coastal-access-england-map.pdf |title=Coastal Access Completion by 2020 \u2013 Provisional Timings and Stretches |publisher=Natural England |date=1 December 2015 |accessdate=4 December 2015}}</ref> \nIn the [[UK]] [[Right_of_way#Foreshore|public access]] to the [[foreshore]], below the line marking [[high tide]], has existed for a long time. The intertidal zone is generally deemed to be owned by the [[The Crown|Crown]] although there are some exceptions. In England ownership of land extends only to the [[High water mark]], and [[The Crown]] is deemed to own what lies below it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.udallaw.com/|title=S.O.U.L.|publisher=|accessdate=13 November 2016}}</ref> \n\nBececause of a European court judgement in April 2018 regarding environmentally protected sites, progress has slowed, though Natural England hope to open \"as much of the England Coast Path as it can by 2020\".<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast#overview-of-progress \"Improving public access to the coast\", England Coast Path, Government of the UK]</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Gristhorpe Cliff Tops on the Cleveland Way.jpg|thumb|right|[[Gristhorpe]] Cliff Tops on the [[Cleveland Way]],  [[North York Moors National Park]].]]\n\nThe final section of a long distance coastal footpath running {{convert|630|mi|km|adj=off}} around the [[South West Coast Path|southwest coast of England]], through Somerset, Devon, Cornwall, Devon and Dorset (walking anti-clockwise) was designated as a [[National Trail]] in 1978.<ref name=\"CA2003\">{{Cite web |url=http://195.92.230.86/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |title=Coast Path is a \u00a3300M Money Spinner for the South West |last=Countryside Agency |date=25 September 2003 |publisher=Countryside Agency |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20081205014058/http://www.countryside.gov.uk/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |archive-date=5 December 2008 |access-date=1 February 2008 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Sections were opened earlier: in Cornwall, 1973, South Devon and Dorset Paths, 1974, Exmoor Coast, 1975.<ref>[https://www.southwestcoastpath.org.uk/about-coast-path/about-us/our-history/ ]\"Our History\", Southwest Coastal Path Association]</ref> \n\nPrior to this, in Wales, the [[Pembrokeshire Coast Path]] had been opened in 1970. Following the establishment of the [[Pembrokeshire Coast National Park]] in 1952, Welsh naturalist and author [[Ronald Lockley]] surveyed a route around the coast. <ref name=\"PembrokeshgireCoastal\">{{cite book |title=The Pembrokeshire Coastal Path: From Amroth to St Dogmaels: A Practical Guide for Walkers |first1=Dennis |last1=Kelsall |first2=Jan |last2=Kelsall |publisher=Cicerone Press |year=2005 |edition=2nd |isbn=978-1852843786}}</ref> Lockley's report for the [[Countryside Commission]] in 1953 was welcomed and broadly adopted. Some sections of the walk were existing rights-of-way, but the majority were in private hands,  necessitating negotiation. Most landowners were in favour, and many benefitted from the erection of new fencing.  Even today, however, the path in places detours from the obvious line where landowners were unwilling to accept a new right-of-way across their land.<ref name=\"PembrokeshireCoast\">{{cite book| title=Pembrokeshire Coast Path |first=Brian |last=John |publisher=Aurum Press |year=2012 |isbn=978-1845137823}}</ref>\n\n===Right to roam===\nin 2000 the Government legislated to introduce a limited ''right to roam'', without compensation for landowners. The [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]] (CROW) was gradually implemented from 2000 onwards to give the general public the conditional right to walk in certain areas of the English and Welsh countryside, including coastal land. Developed land, gardens and certain other areas are specifically excluded from the right of access. Agricultural land is accessible if it falls within one of the categories described in the Act. People exercising the right of access have certain duties to respect other people's rights to manage the land, and to protect nature. The new rights were introduced region by region through England with completion in 2005. Maps showing accessible areas exist.\n\n===Legal background===\n[[File:Cliffs of Dover.jpg|thumb|[[Cliffs of Dover]] on the [[Saxon Shore Way]]]]\nThe England Coast Path has been possible because of the introduction of a UK law, the Right of Coastal Access (Part 9 of the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009)<ref name=\"auto\">{{citation|url=http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/5327964912746496?category=50007|title=Coastal Access - Natural England's Approved Scheme, 2013|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast#map |publisher=www.gov.uk |title= England Coast Path: improving public access to the coast|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref> both along the England Coast Path and, usually, over the associated \u2018coastal margin\u2019.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.gov.uk/manage-your-land-on-the-england-coast-path|publisher= www.gov.uk|title= Manage your land on the England Coast Path|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nNatural England's Coastal Access Scheme was approved by the [[Secretary of State (United Kingdom)|Secretary of State]] on 9 July 2013 under section 298(2) of the [[Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009]], and presented to Parliament pursuant to section 298(6) of the Marine and Coastal Access Act 2009.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe first instance of this new law was implemented on a stretch of the English coast at [[Weymouth Bay]] on 29 June 2012.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/328985/iow-consult-sum-resp.pdf|title=Weymouth Bay|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThis includes \u2013 where appropriate \u2013 any land, other than the trail itself, which forms part of the coastal margin and which has public rights of access along the way. This is known as \u2018spreading room\u2019. However, this does not include any right to enter private houses and gardens or [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] land. The new right of Coastal Access also includes 'roll back', namely that if a section of coast erodes, the path will move back accordingly.<ref name=\"EnglandCoastPath\" />\n\n==Existing coastal trails==\n[[Image:Bamburgh2006.jpg|left|thumb|[[Bamburgh Castle]], on the [[Northumberland]] Coast Trail]]\n{{Main article|List of long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom|National Trails}}\nExisting coastal trails in England will be incorporated into the England Coast Path.  There is, however, work to be done in upgrading and standardizing access and signage on these.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast \"Improving access to the coast\", Natural England].</ref>\n\nThe following is a list of some of the existing coastal paths. For information of others details can be found on the [https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/public/ldp_public_home.php Long Distance Walkers Associations web page].\n\n* [[Bournemouth Coast Path]]: {{convert|20|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[Cleveland Way]]: {{convert|110|mi|km|adj=off}}; only part of the Cleveland Way is coastal. First proposed in the 1930s A formal proposal was submitted in 1953.<ref>The Cleveland Way. Bill Cowley. Dalesman Publishing 1969</ref> The trail was officially opened in 1969. It was the second official [[National Trails|National Trail]] to be opened.<ref>[http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/ClevelandWay/text.asp?PageId=2 About this Trail - Cleveland Way - National Trails<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n* [[Cumbria Coastal Way]]: {{convert|185|mi|km|adj=off}}\n*[[Durham]] Coastal Footpath (18 km/11 miles) passes through or close to [[Seaham Harbour]], [[Dawdon]], [[Easington, County Durham|Easington]], [[Castle Eden Dene|Dene Mouth]], and [[Blackhall]].<ref>[https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Durham+Coastal+Footpath \"Durham Coast Path\", Long Distance Walkers Association]</ref>\n* [[Isle of Wight Coastal Path]]: {{convert|67|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[Lancashire Coastal Way]]: {{convert|66|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[Norfolk Coast Path]]: {{convert|45|mi|km|adj=off}}. It was opened in 1986 and covers the North Norfolk Coast AONB ([[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]).\n* The [[Northumberland Coast]] Path runs 101 km/63 miles along the coast from [[Cresswell, Northumberland|Cresswell]] as far as [[Bamburgh]]. before heading inland to [[Belford, Northumberland|Belford]] and the Kyloe Hills, which offer panoramic coastal views. From here it joins [[St. Cuthbert's Way]] and returns to the coast at the causeway to [[Lindisfarne|Holy Island]] before continuing to [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], close to the Scottish border. It is part of the European [[North Sea Trail]].<ref>[https://www.ldwa.org.uk/ldp/members/show_path.php?path_name=Northumberland+Coast+Path \"Northumberland Coast Path\", Long Distance Walkers Association]</ref>\n* [[Saxon Shore Way]]: {{convert|163|mi|km|adj=off}}. The Saxon Shore Way was originally opened in 1980, but has since been re-established, and in parts re-routed and extended.<ref name=\"Trails and Paths\">{{cite web|url=http://www.walkingpages.co.uk/trails_paths/LDP_saxonshoreway.htm|title=The Saxon Shore Way|publisher=Walking Pages - Trails and Paths|page=1|accessdate=3 April 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080216225018/http://www.walkingpages.co.uk/trails_paths/LDP_saxonshoreway.htm |archivedate = 16 February 2008}}</ref>\n* [[Solent Way]]: {{convert|60|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[South West Coast Path]]: {{convert|630|mi|km|adj=off}}. The final section of the path was designated as a National Trail in 1978.<ref name=\"CA2003\">{{Cite web |url=http://195.92.230.86/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |title=Coast Path is a \u00a3300M Money Spinner for the South West |last=Countryside Agency |date=25 September 2003 |publisher=Countryside Agency |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20081205014058/http://www.countryside.gov.uk/LAR/archive/presscentre/coastpath.asp |archive-date=5 December 2008 |access-date=1 February 2008 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Suffolk Coast Path]]: {{convert|50|mi|km|adj=off}}\n* [[West Somerset Coast Path]]: {{convert|58|mi|km|adj=off}}. In March 2016 the path was extended to run from [[Brean Down]] to [[Minehead]].<ref>{{cite web|title=England Coast Path new stretch opens in Somerset|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-35810243|publisher=BBC|accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Work in progress===\n[[Image:Head banner cropped golf2.jpg|350px|thumb|[[St Bees Head]], [[Cumbria Coastal Way]]]]\n\nSee the official website for the current situations: [https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast Natural England]. Some [[right of way]] and foreshore access may already exist.\n\n===Linked trails===\n\n*At the border with [[Wales]] it will link to the [[Wales Coast Path]], which was fully opened on 5 May 2012, and comprises an {{convert|870|mi|adj=on}} coastal walking route from [[Chepstow]] in the south to [[Queensferry, Flintshire|Queensferry]] in the north.<ref name=\"BBCNews20111017\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-15283462|work=BBC News Wales |title= All-Wales coast path nears completion|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/uk/a-welsh-wander-tackle-the-870-milelong-wales-coast-path-a-little-at-a-time-7712412.html|work=The Independent|title= Wales Coast Path at a glance|accessdate=16 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n*[[Offa's Dyke Path]], a {{convert|177|mi|km|adj=on}} non-coastal route, also links the England Coast Path at its Welsh border, largely following the line of the remnants of [[Offa's Dyke]], fairly close to the boundary between England and Wales.\n\n==outline of the route==\nNatural England has divided the coast into 66 sections for planning purposes. The sections fall into 5 categories:\n* England Coast Path and associated access rights now open\n* Approved but not yet open\n* Work in progress\n* Estimated start 2016\u201317\n* Estimated start 2017\u201318\n\nThe sections (working anti-clockwise round England from the southern end of the Welsh border and using Natural England's areas) comprise:<ref name=\"Progress\" />\n\n{{Flatlist|\n* '''Area 11: [[Somerset]]'''\n** [[Aust]] to [[Brean Down]]\n** Brean Down to [[Minehead]]\n* '''Area 12: [[Devon]] and [[Cornwall]]'''\n** Minehead to [[Combe Martin]]\n** [[South West Coast Path]]\n** [[St Anthony in Roseland|St Anthony]] to [[Cremyll]]\n** [[Kingswear]] to [[Lyme Regis]]\n* '''Area 13: [[Dorset]], [[Hampshire]] and [[Isle of Wight]]'''\n** Lyme Regis to [[Rufus Castle]]\n** Rufus Castle to [[Lulworth Cove]]\n** Lulworth Cove to [[Christchurch, Dorset|Christchurch]]\n** Christchurch to [[Calshot]]\n** Calshot to [[Gosport]]\n** [[Isle of Wight]]\n** Gosport to South Hayling Island\n* '''Area 14: [[Sussex]] and [[Kent]]'''\n** [[South Hayling]] Island to East Head\n** East Head to [[Shoreham-by-Sea|Shoreham]]\n** Shoreham to [[Eastbourne]]\n** Eastbourne to [[Camber, East Sussex|Camber]]\n** Camber to [[Folkestone]]\n** Folkestone to [[Ramsgate]]\n** Ramsgate to [[Whitstable]]\n** [[Isle of Sheppey]]\n** Whitstable to [[Iwade]]\n** Iwade to [[Grain, Kent|Grain]]\n** Grain to [[Gravesend]]\n* '''Area 8: [[Essex]]'''\n** Gravesend to [[Southend-on-Sea]]\n** Southend to [[Wallasea Island]]\n** [[Foulness]], [[Potton Island|Potton]] and Wallasea Island\n** Wallasea Island to [[Burnham-on-Crouch]]\n** Burnham-on-Crouch to [[Maldon, Essex|Maldon]]\n** Maldon to [[Salcott]]\n** [[Mersea Island]]\n** Salcott to [[Jaywick]]\n** Jaywick to [[Harwich]]\n* '''Area 9: [[Suffolk]] and [[Norfolk]]'''\n** Harwich to [[Shotley Gate]]\n** Shotley Gate to [[Felixstowe]]\n** [[Felixstowe Ferry]] to [[Bawdsey]]\n** Bawdsey to [[Aldeburgh]]\n** Aldeburgh to [[Hopton-on-Sea]]\n** Hopton-on-Sea to [[Sea Palling]]\n** Sea Palling to [[Weybourne, Norfolk|Weybourne]]\n** Weybourne to [[Hunstanton]]\n** Hunstanton to [[Sutton Bridge]]\n* '''Area 5: [[Lincolnshire]]'''\n** Sutton Bridge to [[Skegness]]\n** Skegness to [[Donna Nook]]\n** '''''Area 3''''' ([[Yorkshire]])\n** Donna Nook to [[Humber Bridge]]\n** Humber Bridge to [[Kilnsea]]\n** Kilnsea to [[Filey Brigg]]\n** Filey Brigg to [[Tees Newport Bridge|Newport Bridge]]\n* '''Area 1: [[County Durham|Durham]], [[Tyne & Wear]] and [[Northumberland]]'''\n** Newport Bridge to North Gare\n** North Gare to South Bents\n** South Bents to [[Amble]]\n** Amble to [[Bamburgh]]\n** [[Lindisfarne]]\n** Bamburgh to [[Anglo-Scottish border|Scottish border]]\n** '''''Area 2''''' ([[Cumbria]])\n** [[Lindisfarne|Gretna]] to [[Allonby]]\n** Allonby to [[Whitehaven]]\n** Whitehaven to [[Silecroft]]\n** Silecroft to [[Silverdale, Lancashire|Silverdale]]\n* '''Area 4: [[Lancashire]] and [[Merseyside]]'''\n** [[Walney Island]]\n** Silverdale to [[Cleveleys]]\n** Cleveleys to [[Pier Head]], [[Liverpool]]\n** [[Birkenhead]] to Welsh Border\n}}\n\n==See also==\n\n* The [[E9 European long distance path]] or European Coastal Path (French: ''Sentier Europ\u00e9en du Littoral'') is one of the [[European long-distance paths]], running for {{convert|5000|km}} from [[Cabo de S\u00e3o Vicente]] in [[Portugal]] to [[Narva-J\u00f5esuu]] in [[Estonia]]. UK Section [[Dover]] to [[Plymouth]] (both ferry ports).\n* [[Long-distance footpaths in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[North Sea Trail]]. In England partner areas are [[Northumberland]], and the [[North York Moors]]\n* [[Scottish Coastal Way]]\n\n==References== \n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/england-coast-path-improving-public-access-to-the-coast England Coast Path: improving public access to the coast] Natural England. Retrieved 20 January 2017\n* [http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/england-coast-path England Coast Path] National Trails. Retrieved 20 January 2017\n\n{{Coastal paths of Britain}}\n{{UK Trails}}\n\n[[Category:Coastal paths in England]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Rwood128", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caption", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/England_Coast_Path"}
{"title_page": "Michael D. Aeschliman", "text_new": "'''Michael D. Aeschliman''' (born 21 September 1948), is a U.S.-Swiss educator, literary critic and scholar, Professor Emeritus at Boston University, Professor of Anglophone Culture at the ''Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana'' (University of Italian Switzerland)<ref>https://www.bu.edu/wheelock/profile/michael-aeschliman/</ref> and Curriculum Advisor to the American College of Switzerland Foundation Board.<ref>https://www.tasis.com/page.cfm?p=276</ref> He previously taught at the University of Virginia (1985-1993).<ref>https://www.brown.edu/Departments/Italian_Studies/LD/numbers/02/aeschliman.html</ref> Aeschliman holds B.A., M.A., M.Phil., and Ph.D. degrees from Columbia University. He is the author of ''The Restoration of Man: C. S. Lewis and the Continuing Case against Scientism'' (3rd. edition, 2019; translated into French, 2020), which has been described by ''The National Review'' as \"a book marked by tremendous learning worn lightly, deployed vigorously, and offered generously to a generation that has forgotten how to think because it has lost its grip on the meaning of words.\"<ref>https://www.nationalreview.com/magazine/2019/09/30/c-s-lewis-and-the-religion-of-science/</ref> The major French daily newspaper ''Le Figaro'' also hailed its publication, describing it as a work that \"at long last makes accessible to the general reading public the essential reflections of C. S. Lewis on scientism and transhumanism.\"<ref>https://www.lefigaro.fr/vox/culture/quand-l-auteur-de-narnia-ecrivait-contre-le-transhumanisme-20200306</ref> The first edition was prefaced by the prominent journalist and intellectual Malcolm Muggeridge and praised by Russell Kirk as \u201cOne of the most perceptive books on C. S. Lewis,\u201d and \u201cA succinct, strong book, worthy of Lewis himself.\u201d<ref>https://evolutionnews.org/2019/09/from-national-review-a-rave-for-aeschliman-on-the-religion-of-science/</ref> Aeschliman writes regularly on educational and cultural topics for several American magazines, including ''National Review'', ''First Things''<ref>https://www.firstthings.com/article/1990/08/solzhenitsyn-and-modern-literature</ref>, ''Modern Age''<ref>https://isi.org/modern-age/faustian-fantasist-and-fraud/</ref>, and ''The Journal of Education'' (Boston).<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/42742591?seq=1</ref> He is featured in the film \"The Magician's Twin: C.S. Lewis and the Case against Scientism\" (2012)<ref>https://www.discovery.org/v/the-magicians-twin/</ref><ref>https://www.movieguide.org/reviews/the-magicians-twin.html</ref> In 2012, Aeschliman authored a new critical edition of Charles Dickens' ''A Tale of Two Cities''.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Tale-Cities-Ignatius-Critical-Editions/dp/1586174428</ref>\n", "text_old": "'''Michael D. Aeschliman''' (born 21 September 1948), is a U.S.-Swiss educator, literary critic and scholar, Professor Emeritus at Boston University, Professor of Anglophone Culture at the ''Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana'' (University of Italian Switzerland)<ref>https://www.bu.edu/wheelock/profile/michael-aeschliman/</ref> and Curriculum Advisor to the the American College of Switzerland Foundation Board.<ref>https://www.tasis.com/page.cfm?p=276</ref> He previously taught at the University of Virginia (1985-1993).<ref>https://www.brown.edu/Departments/Italian_Studies/LD/numbers/02/aeschliman.html</ref> Aeschliman holds B.A., M.A., M.Phil., and Ph.D. degrees from Columbia University. He is the author of ''The Restoration of Man: C. S. Lewis and the Continuing Case against Scientism'' (3rd. edition, 2019; translated into French, 2020), which has been described by ''The National Review'' as \"a book marked by tremendous learning worn lightly, deployed vigorously, and offered generously to a generation that has forgotten how to think because it has lost its grip on the meaning of words.\"<ref>https://www.nationalreview.com/magazine/2019/09/30/c-s-lewis-and-the-religion-of-science/</ref> The major French daily newspaper ''Le Figaro'' also hailed its publication, describing it as a work that \"at long last makes accessible to the general reading public the essential reflections of C. S. Lewis on scientism and transhumanism.\"<ref>https://www.lefigaro.fr/vox/culture/quand-l-auteur-de-narnia-ecrivait-contre-le-transhumanisme-20200306</ref> The first edition was prefaced by the prominent journalist and intellectual Malcolm Muggeridge and praised by Russell Kirk as \u201cOne of the most perceptive books on C. S. Lewis,\u201d and \u201cA succinct, strong book, worthy of Lewis himself.\u201d<ref>https://evolutionnews.org/2019/09/from-national-review-a-rave-for-aeschliman-on-the-religion-of-science/</ref> Aeschliman writes regularly on educational and cultural topics for several American magazines, including ''National Review'', ''First Things''<ref>https://www.firstthings.com/article/1990/08/solzhenitsyn-and-modern-literature</ref>, ''Modern Age''<ref>https://isi.org/modern-age/faustian-fantasist-and-fraud/</ref>, and ''The Journal of Education'' (Boston).<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/42742591?seq=1</ref> He is featured in the film \"The Magician's Twin: C.S. Lewis and the Case against Scientism\" (2012)<ref>https://www.discovery.org/v/the-magicians-twin/</ref><ref>https://www.movieguide.org/reviews/the-magicians-twin.html</ref> In 2012, Aeschliman authored a new critical edition of Charles Dickens' ''A Tale of Two Cities''.<ref>https://www.amazon.com/Tale-Cities-Ignatius-Critical-Editions/dp/1586174428</ref>\n", "name_user": "A. Roderick-Grove", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removal of redundant article (\"the\")", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_D._Aeschliman"}
{"title_page": "Raymond Lee (soccer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Raymond Lee\n| image = CINvPGH 2018-04-21 - Ray Lee (27992691608) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Lee with Pittsburgh Riverhounds in 2018\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Kansas City, Missouri]], United States\n| height = 5 ft 11 in\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[Chattanooga FC]] and [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| clubnumber = 2 and 3\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20132011\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| collegeyears1 = 2011\u20132014\n| college1 = [[Saint Louis Billikens men's soccer|Saint Louis Billikens]]\n| collegecaps1 = 75\n| collegegoals1 = 12\n| years1 = 2015\n| clubs1 = [[Philadelphia Union]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2015\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Harrisburg City Islanders]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 2\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2016\n| clubs3 = [[FC Tulsa (USL)|Tulsa Roughnecks]]\n| caps3 = 19\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2017\n| clubs4 = [[Rochester Rhinos]]\n| caps4 = 14\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2018\n| clubs6 = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| years6 = 2018\n| clubs7 = [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC]]\n| caps7 = 28\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2019\n| clubs8 = [[Hartford Athletic]]\n| caps8 = 30\n| goals8 = 1\n| years9 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs9 = [[Chattanooga FC]]\n| caps9 = 1\n| goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2018-\n| clubs10 = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| caps10 = 14\n| goals10 = 11\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| medaltemplates = \n| club-update = April 7, 2020\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Raymond Lee''' (born April 26, 1993) is an American professional [[association football|soccer]] and [[Major Arena Soccer League]] player who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for [[Chattanooga FC]] in the [[National Independent Soccer Association]] and the [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] in the [[Major Arena Soccer League]].\n\n==Career==\n===Amateur===\nLee played four years of [[college soccer]] at the [[University of Saint Louis]] between 2011 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slubillikens.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205263518|title=Raymond Lee Biography|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to college, Lee played for the academy of [[Sporting Kansas City]].\n\n===Professional===\nOn January 20, 2015, Lee was picked 71st overall in the [[2015 MLS SuperDraft]] by [[Philadelphia Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philadelphiaunion.com/news/2015/01/philadelphia-union-add-defensive-depth-tuesdays-rounds-3-4-2015-mls-superdraft |title=Philadelphia Union add defensive depth in Tuesday's rounds 3-4 of 2015 MLS SuperDraft|publisher=Philadelphia Union |date=2015-01-20 |accessdate=2018-05-14}}</ref> Lee signed with Philadelphia on March 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=Philadelphia Union Communications |url=http://www.philadelphiaunion.com/news/2015/03/philadelphia-union-sign-raymond-lee-and-eric-ayuk-mbu |title=Philadelphia Union Sign Raymond Lee and Eric Ayuk Mbu|publisher=Philadelphia Union |date=2015-03-03 |accessdate=2018-05-14}}</ref>\n\nLee signed with [[United Soccer League]] side [[Bethlehem Steel FC|Bethlehem Steel]] on January 29, 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=32800&ATCLID=210672417 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201025110/http://www.uslsoccer.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=32800&ATCLID=210672417 |archivedate=2016-02-01 }}</ref> but was released by the club before the start of the season after falling down the depth chart at left back.<ref>{{cite web|last=Villella|first=Evan|url=https://www.brotherlygame.com/2016/3/24/11302260/raymond-lee-and-bethlehem-steel-fc-part-ways|title=Raymond Lee and Bethlehem Steel FC part ways|website=BrotherlyGame.com|publisher=SB Nation|accessdate=April 17, 2019|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> He instead joined [[FC Tulsa (USL)|Tulsa Roughnecks]] on March 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/629643?referrer_id=2382812|title=Roughnecks Make Pair of Defensive Signings|first=USLSoccer.com|last=Staff|date=25 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nLee joined USL side [[Rochester Rhinos]] in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/rochester-rhinos-roster|title=Rochester Rhinos Roster - uslsoccer.com|website=www.uslsoccer.com}}</ref>\n\nLee signed with USL side [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC]] on December 15, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riverhounds.com/news_article/show/867090?referrer_id=2869741|title=Hounds sign new additions in Fran\u00e7ois, Lee|first=Riverhounds|last=Staff|date=15 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2019, Lee joined USL Championship club [[Hartford Athletic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Four Players Join Hartford Athletic |url=https://www.hartfordathletic.com/news_article/show/985676 |website=HartfordAthletic.com |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Honors===\n;Individual\n*MASL All-Rookie First Team: 2019-20<ref>{{cite web |title=2019-20 ALL-MASL ROOKIE TEAM ANNOUNCED |url=https://www.maslsoccer.com/news/2019-2020-all-masl-rookie-team-announced |website=MASL |publisher=Soccer Shift |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{MLS player}}\n* {{USL player}}\n* {{Soccerway|raymond-lee/401579}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Raymond}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis Billikens men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Union players]]\n[[Category:Penn FC players]]\n[[Category:Bethlehem Steel FC players]]\n[[Category:FC Tulsa players]]\n[[Category:Rochester Rhinos players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC players]]\n[[Category:Hartford Athletic players]]\n[[Category:Chattanooga FC players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Soccer players from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Union draft picks]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:USL Championship players]]\n[[Category:National Independent Soccer Association players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Raymond Lee\n| image = CINvPGH 2018-04-21 - Ray Lee (27992691608) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Lee with Pittsburgh Riverhounds in 2018\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1993|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Kansas City, Missouri]], United States\n| height = 5 ft 11 in\n| position = [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]\n| currentclub = [[Chattanooga FC]] and [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| clubnumber = 2 and 3\n| youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}\u20132011\n| youthclubs1 = [[Sporting Kansas City]]\n| collegeyears1 = 2011\u20132014\n| college1 = [[Saint Louis Billikens men's soccer|Saint Louis Billikens]]\n| collegecaps1 = 75\n| collegegoals1 = 12\n| years1 = 2015\n| clubs1 = [[Philadelphia Union]]\n| caps1 = 1\n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2015\n| clubs2 = \u2192 [[Harrisburg City Islanders]] (loan)\n| caps2 = 2\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2016\n| clubs3 = [[FC Tulsa (USL)|Tulsa Roughnecks]]\n| caps3 = 19\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2017\n| clubs4 = [[Rochester Rhinos]]\n| caps4 = 14\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2018\n| clubs6 = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| years6 = 2018\n| clubs7 = [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC]]\n| caps7 = 28\n| goals7 = 0\n| years8 = 2019\n| clubs8 = [[Hartford Athletic]]\n| caps8 = 30\n| goals8 = 1\n| years9 = 2020\u2013\n| clubs9 = [[Chattanooga FC]]\n| caps9 = 1\n| goals9 = 0\n| years10 = 2018-\n| clubs10 = [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]]\n| caps10 = 14\n| goals10 = 11\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| medaltemplates = \n| club-update = April 7, 2020\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Raymond Lee''' (born April 26, 1993) is an American professional [[association football|soccer]] and [[Major Arena Soccer League]] player who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for [[Chattanooga FC]] in the [[National Independent Soccer Association]] and the [[Kansas City Comets (2010\u2013)|Kansas City Comets]] in the [[Major Arena Soccer League]].\n\n==Career==\n===Amateur===\nLee played four years of [[college soccer]] at the [[University of Saint Louis]] between 2011 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slubillikens.com/ViewArticle.dbml?ATCLID=205263518|title=Raymond Lee Biography|publisher=}}</ref> Prior to college, Lee played for the academy of [[Sporting Kansas City]].\n\n===Professional===\nOn January 20, 2015, Lee was picked 71st overall in the [[2015 MLS SuperDraft]] by [[Philadelphia Union]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philadelphiaunion.com/news/2015/01/philadelphia-union-add-defensive-depth-tuesdays-rounds-3-4-2015-mls-superdraft |title=Philadelphia Union add defensive depth in Tuesday's rounds 3-4 of 2015 MLS SuperDraft|publisher=Philadelphia Union |date=2015-01-20 |accessdate=2018-05-14}}</ref> Lee signed with Philadelphia on March 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=Philadelphia Union Communications |url=http://www.philadelphiaunion.com/news/2015/03/philadelphia-union-sign-raymond-lee-and-eric-ayuk-mbu |title=Philadelphia Union Sign Raymond Lee and Eric Ayuk Mbu|publisher=Philadelphia Union |date=2015-03-03 |accessdate=2018-05-14}}</ref>\n\nLee signed with [[United Soccer League]] side [[Bethlehem Steel FC|Bethlehem Steel]] on January 29, 2016,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=32800&ATCLID=210672417 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160201025110/http://www.uslsoccer.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=32800&ATCLID=210672417 |archivedate=2016-02-01 }}</ref> but was released by the club before the start of the season after falling down the depth chart at left back.<ref>{{cite web|last=Villella|first=Evan|url=https://www.brotherlygame.com/2016/3/24/11302260/raymond-lee-and-bethlehem-steel-fc-part-ways|title=Raymond Lee and Bethlehem Steel FC part ways|website=BrotherlyGame.com|publisher=SB Nation|accessdate=April 17, 2019|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> He instead joined [[FC Tulsa (USL)|Tulsa Roughnecks]] on March 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/629643?referrer_id=2382812|title=Roughnecks Make Pair of Defensive Signings|first=USLSoccer.com|last=Staff|date=25 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nLee joined USL side [[Rochester Rhinos]] in March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/rochester-rhinos-roster|title=Rochester Rhinos Roster - uslsoccer.com|website=www.uslsoccer.com}}</ref>\n\nLee signed with USL side [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds SC]] on December 15, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.riverhounds.com/news_article/show/867090?referrer_id=2869741|title=Hounds sign new additions in Fran\u00e7ois, Lee|first=Riverhounds|last=Staff|date=15 December 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2019, Lee joined USL Championship club [[Hartford Athletic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Four Players Join Hartford Athletic |url=https://www.hartfordathletic.com/news_article/show/985676 |website=HartfordAthletic.com |accessdate=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{MLS player}}\n* {{USL player}}\n* {{Soccerway|raymond-lee/401579}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lee, Raymond}}\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:American soccer players]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis Billikens men's soccer players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Union players]]\n[[Category:Penn FC players]]\n[[Category:Bethlehem Steel FC players]]\n[[Category:FC Tulsa players]]\n[[Category:Rochester Rhinos pl