{"title_page": "Suze Morrison", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Suze Morrison\n| image         = File:Suze Morrison.png\n| caption       =\n| honorific-suffix       = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]]\n| parliament3   = Ontario Provincial\n| term_start3   = June 7, 2018\n| term_end3      =\n| predecessor3  = [[Glen Murray (politician)|Glen Murray]]\n| successor3    =\n| riding3       = [[Toronto Centre (provincial electoral district)|Toronto Centre]]\n| party         = [[Ontario New Democratic Party|New Democratic]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1988|02|04}}\n| birth_place   = [[Parry Sound District]], [[Ontario]]\n| residence     = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| occupation    = Communications consultant \n|alma_mater     = [[University of Guelph-Humber]]\n| spouse        = Trevor Morey<ref name=lemard>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/homicide-victim-cpr-1.4188612 \"Man killed in Regent Park drive-by shooting ID'd as Lemard Champagnie\"]. [[CBC News]] Toronto, July 3, 2017.</ref>\n| children      = \n}}\n\n'''Suze Morrison''' is a [[Canada|Canadian]] politician, who was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] in the [[2018 Ontario general election|2018 provincial election]].<ref name=historic>{{cite news |last1=Ormsby |first1=Mary |title=Historic NDP win as Suze Morrison takes Toronto Centre |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2018/06/07/ndps-suze-morrison-ahead.html|accessdate=June 8, 2018 |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=June 7, 2018}}</ref> She represents the riding of [[Toronto Centre (provincial electoral district)|Toronto Centre]] as a member of the [[Ontario New Democratic Party]], and is the Ontario New Democratic Party's Caucus Critic for both Housing and Women's Issues.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ontariondp.ca/sites/default/files/18-0820critic20portfolios-3.pdf|title=NDP Caucus Critic Portfolios - August 2018|date=August 2018|website=www.ontariondp.ca|access-date=2018-12-20}}</ref>\n\n== Background == \nOf mixed European and Indigenous heritage, Morrison was born in the [[Parry Sound District]] before moving to [[Toronto]] in childhood. She took her [[Bachelor of Applied Arts|B.A.A]] degree in media studies from [[University of Guelph-Humber|Guelph-Humber]], and has worked in communications and public relations in the non-profit sector.<ref name=historic/> She first became prominent within the riding as an advocate for community safety after witnessing the drive-by shooting of Lemard Champagnie in Toronto's [[Regent Park]] neighbourhood in 2017.<ref name=lemard/>\n\nMorrison is a motorsports enthusiast, and competes in [[autocross]] events. She is a two-time winner of the Lorna Wilson Ladies Championship, which is awarded by the Western Ontario Sports Car Association.<ref>[http://wosca.ca/results/ \"WOSCA Results\"]</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\nDuring the election campaign, she participated alongside Liberal MPP [[Steven Del Duca]] and Progressive Conservative MPP [[Lisa Thompson (politician)|Lisa Thompson]] in Election Brew, a non-partisan event sponsored by [[Equal Voice]] and [[Labatt]] to increase citizen engagement in politics through a friendly competition to create [[craft beer]] brews; Morrison's beer, an [[India pale ale]], won the competition.<ref>\"With provincial election brewing, Labatt brings political foes together\". ''[[Canada NewsWire]]'', May 2, 2018.</ref>\n\nShe was one of three MPPs of Indigenous heritage elected in 2018, alongside caucus colleagues [[Guy Bourgouin]] and [[Sol Mamakwa]].<ref>[https://ici.radio-canada.ca/espaces-autochtones/a-la-une/document/nouvelles/article/1105824/premiere-nation-autochtone-election-ontario-depute-npd \"Sol Mamakwa, seul membre d'une Premi\u00e8re Nation \u00e0 Queen's Park\"]. [[Ici Radio-Canada]] Espaces autochtones, June 8, 2018.</ref>\n\nShe serves as a member of the Standing Committee on Public Accounts,<ref>[https://www.ola.org/en/members/all/suze-morrison \"Ontario Legislature\"]. August 24, 2018</ref> and as the official opposition critic for housing and women's issues.\n\n===Electoral record===\n{{CANelec/top|ON|2018|Toronto Centre (provincial electoral district)|Toronto Centre|percent=yes|change=yes|prelim=no}}\n{{CANelec|ON|NDP|Suze Morrison|23,688|53.66| +37.87}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Liberal|David Morris|11,986|27.15| -31.07}}\n{{CANelec|ON|PC|Meredith Cartwright|6,234|14.12| -4.43}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Green|Adam Sommerfeld|1,377|3.12| -1.30}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Libertarian|Judi Falardeau|371|0.84| -0.23}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Special Needs|Dan King|117|0.27| -0.12}}\n{{CANelec|ON|New People's Choice|Cameron James|110|0.25|}}\n{{CANelec|ON|[[Stop the New Sex-Ed Agenda]]|Theresa Snell|102|0.23|}}\n{{CANelec|ON|[[The People's Political Party|The People]]|[[Kevin Clarke (politician)|Kevin Clarke]]|98|0.22| +0.06}}\n{{CANelec|ON|Canadian Economic|Wanda Marie Fountain|65|0.15|}}\n{{CANelec/total|Total valid votes|44,148|100.0 &nbsp;}}<!--\n{{CANelec/total|Total rejected, unmarked and declined ballots|||}}\n{{CANelec/total|Turnout|||}}\n{{CANelec/total|Eligible voters|}}-->\n{{CANelec/gain|ON|NDP|Liberal| +34.47}}\n{{CANelec/source|Source: [[Elections Ontario]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elections.on.ca/content/dam/NGW/sitecontent/2018/results/officialresults-yellowbook/votescastbycandidate/pdf/Valid%20Votes%20Cast%20for%20Each%20Candidate%20-%202018%20Provincial%20General%20Election.pdf|title=Summary of Valid Votes Cast for each Candidate |page=11|publisher=Elections Ontario|accessdate=20 January 2019}}</ref>}}\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Ontario MPPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morrison, Suze}}\n[[Category:Ontario New Democratic Party MPPs]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women MPPs in Ontario]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Toronto]]\n[[Category:First Nations women in politics]]\n[[Category:University of Guelph alumni]]\n[[Category:1988 